ninjabackend: pass objects to doctests

Fix my misunderstanding of the code before commit aede231ef ("ninjabackend:
pass objects to generate_rust_target from non-Rust sources", 2025-07-29).

Object files were added by get_rust_compiler_deps_and_args() to both the
main target and the doctest command lines:

        objs, od = self.flatten_object_list(target)
        for o in objs:
            args.append(f'-Clink-arg={o}')
            deps.append(o)

therefore they now need to be passed as the final argument of
get_rust_compiler_deps_and_args() for both command lines as well.
Failure to do so causes problems building doctests when the main
target has objects as well.

Add a regression test as well.

This pull request introduces significant improvements to the project's development workflow, documentation, and configuration management. It adds comprehensive developer documentation, modernizes the CI/CD pipeline, introduces pre-commit hooks, and refines environment and Docker setup for consistency and best practices. Additionally, it includes a database migration and minor codebase improvements.

**Developer Experience & Documentation:**

- Added a detailed `CLAUDE.md` file describing the architecture, setup, commands, testing, and best practices for the project, making onboarding and contribution easier.
- Introduced a `Makefile` with targets for installation, testing, linting, formatting, Docker management, and more, streamlining common development tasks.

**Continuous Integration & Quality:**

- Added a GitHub Actions workflow (`.github/workflows/test.yml`) that runs linting, formatting, type checking, unit/integration/e2e/performance tests, and uploads coverage reports, ensuring high code quality and reliability.
- Introduced `.pre-commit-config.yaml` to enforce code quality and consistency with hooks for linting, formatting, type checking, and running tests before commits and pushes.

**Configuration & Environment:**

- Overhauled `.env.example` to group variables by theme, add missing options, clarify usage, and improve naming consistency.
- Updated `Dockerfile` to use the `uv` base image, install dependencies with `uv`, and run the bot using `uv`, aligning Docker with the local dev environment.

**Database & Codebase:**

- Added an Alembic migration to change the `is_captcha_enabled` column in the `chats` table from `INTEGER` to `BOOLEAN`, improving data integrity.
- Updated Alembic environment configuration to use the new settings import and variable names. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-cd4d26a53ff97e019b612811dfa604ba24d5dfd2f4dc1b195f3e74d85c38e630L8-R8) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-cd4d26a53ff97e019b612811dfa604ba24d5dfd2f4dc1b195f3e74d85c38e630L31-R31)
- Minor code improvement: added type annotation for the `db` parameter in `save_message` and reordered imports for clarity.

**Other:**

- Added `/blacklist` command to the user-facing documentation.

These changes collectively modernize the project's tooling, improve maintainability, and make it easier for new contributors to get started.

pull_request.title: [Graph Vis] Implement Minimap
pull_request.body:
## Summary Closes: - https://github.com/elastic/kibana/issues/222381 ### Screenshots #### Without minimap Regular graph with hidden Minimap #### No interactive graph Minimap and Controls not visible, nodes are not clickable, graph is not pannable #### Locked graph Minimap and Controls visible, nodes are clickable but graph is not pannable #### Regular graph Minimap and Controls visible, nodes are clickable, graph is pannable #### Large graph Same as before but with a higher number of nodes #### Graph with unknown node type Minimap renders "fallback" minimap node when node data type is not supported (not an _entity_ nor _label_ nor _stack_ node) ### Spec for LLM
Spec Write a detailed feature development plan for my next feature: Add a minimap to our graph. #### Context and Motivation I'm using `xyflow/react` for the implementation of our Graph component. It renders multiple nodes and edges. However, as the graph grows in complexity and size, users need a better way to orient themselves within the canvas. A minimap will allow users to quickly understand the graph structure and navigate to specific areas more efficiently, improving the overall usability and scalability of the visualization. #### Definition of done - Create a `Minimap` component in `x-pack/solutions/security/packages/kbn-cloud-security-posture/graph/src/components/minimap/minimap.tsx` - Render `Minimap` component in `x-pack/solutions/security/packages/kbn-cloud-security-posture/graph/src/components/graph/graph.tsx` among with other graph parts i.e. `Background` - Add a new button to `Controls` component to toggle on/off the Minimap - `Minimap` will be off by default but will render if the new Minimap button in `Controls` was toggled on - `Minimap` must render the existing graph with the same nodes, edges and positions, but in a much smaller scale - `Minimap` must be located at the bottom-left corner of the Graph. It should be a floating element, similar to our `Controls` component. - Minimap must be pannable and zoomable. Set zoom speed to 2 - Clicking on the minimap must automatically move the `Graph`'s position - Dragging on the minimap must automatically move the `Graph`'s position dragging in scale - Create a new Storybook page to render the minimap alone - Create a new Storybook page to render both the `Graph` and `Minimap`. It will allow us to see how they're integrated and test clicking and dragging on the minimap really reflects changes in the graph - Create unit tests for `Minimap` in `x-pack/solutions/security/packages/kbn-cloud-security-posture/graph/src/components/minimap/minimap.test.tsx`. Think of all possible test cases. Some I've thought of are: - Minimap exists but is empty with empty input (no nodes and no edges) - Minimap renders some nodes and edges matching its input - Minimap renders nodes with different colors when input contains nodes with different color props - Add integration tests to `x-pack/solutions/security/packages/kbn-cloud-security-posture/graph/src/components/graph/graph.test.tsx`: - Minimap is empty when Graph is empty - Minimap renders some nodes and edges matching graph's nodes and edges - Clicking on a specific coordinate of the Minimap moves the Graph to the exact same scaled position - Dragging on a specific coordinate of the Minimap moves the Graph to the exact same scaled position

pull_request.body:
## Summary Closes: - https://github.com/elastic/kibana/issues/222381 ### Screenshots #### Without minimap Regular graph with hidden Minimap #### No interactive graph Minimap and Controls not visible, nodes are not clickable, graph is not pannable #### Locked graph Minimap and Controls visible, nodes are clickable but graph is not pannable #### Regular graph Minimap and Controls visible, nodes are clickable, graph is pannable #### Large graph Same as before but with a higher number of nodes #### Graph with unknown node type Minimap renders "fallback" minimap node when node data type is not supported (not an _entity_ nor _label_ nor _stack_ node) ### Spec for LLM
Spec Write a detailed feature development plan for my next feature: Add a minimap to our graph. #### Context and Motivation I'm using `xyflow/react` for the implementation of our Graph component. It renders multiple nodes and edges. However, as the graph grows in complexity and size, users need a better way to orient themselves within the canvas. A minimap will allow users to quickly understand the graph structure and navigate to specific areas more efficiently, improving the overall usability and scalability of the visualization. #### Definition of done - Create a `Minimap` component in `x-pack/solutions/security/packages/kbn-cloud-security-posture/graph/src/components/minimap/minimap.tsx` - Render `Minimap` component in `x-pack/solutions/security/packages/kbn-cloud-security-posture/graph/src/components/graph/graph.tsx` among with other graph parts i.e. `Background` - Add a new button to `Controls` component to toggle on/off the Minimap - `Minimap` will be off by default but will render if the new Minimap button in `Controls` was toggled on - `Minimap` must render the existing graph with the same nodes, edges and positions, but in a much smaller scale - `Minimap` must be located at the bottom-left corner of the Graph. It should be a floating element, similar to our `Controls` component. - Minimap must be pannable and zoomable. Set zoom speed to 2 - Clicking on the minimap must automatically move the `Graph`'s position - Dragging on the minimap must automatically move the `Graph`'s position dragging in scale - Create a new Storybook page to render the minimap alone - Create a new Storybook page to render both the `Graph` and `Minimap`. It will allow us to see how they're integrated and test clicking and dragging on the minimap really reflects changes in the graph - Create unit tests for `Minimap` in `x-pack/solutions/security/packages/kbn-cloud-security-posture/graph/src/components/minimap/minimap.test.tsx`. Think of all possible test cases. Some I've thought of are: - Minimap exists but is empty with empty input (no nodes and no edges) - Minimap renders some nodes and edges matching its input - Minimap renders nodes with different colors when input contains nodes with different color props - Add integration tests to `x-pack/solutions/security/packages/kbn-cloud-security-posture/graph/src/components/graph/graph.test.tsx`: - Minimap is empty when Graph is empty - Minimap renders some nodes and edges matching graph's nodes and edges - Clicking on a specific coordinate of the Minimap moves the Graph to the exact same scaled position - Dragging on a specific coordinate of the Minimap moves the Graph to the exact same scaled position
